description: From Ancient Greek ἐννεάς (enneás), ἐννεάδος (enneádos, “body of nine”)  +‎ -ad (suffix designating a unit); analysable as ennea- +‎ -ad. The Greek words ἐννεάς and ἐννεάδος are derived from ἐννέᾰ (ennéa, “nine”) (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₁néwn̥ (“nine”)) + -ᾰ́ς (-ás, suffix forming abstract nouns of number from numerals) or -ος (-os).

entries.meaning: (rare) Any grouping or system containing nine objects.
